In this table:
*The semigroup ({0,1}, <math>\wedge</math>) denotes the two-element semigroup containing the [[Null semigroup#Zero element in a semigroup|zero element]] 0 and the [[unit element]] 1.  The two binary operations defined by matrices in a green background are associative and pairing either with ''A'' creates a semigroup isomorphic to the semigroup ({0,1}, <math>\wedge</math>). Every element is [[idempotent]] in this semigroup, so it is a [[Band (mathematics)|band]]. Furthermore, it is commutative (abelian) and thus a [[semilattice]]. The [[Semilattice#Connection_between_both_definitions|order induced]] is a [[linear order]], and so it is in fact a [[Lattice (order)|lattice]] and it is also a [[Distributive lattice|distributive]] and [[complemented lattice]], i.e. it is actually the [[two-element Boolean algebra]].
*The two binary operations defined by matrices in a blue background are associative and pairing either with ''A'' creates a semigroup isomorphic to the [[null semigroup]] O<sub>2</sub> with two elements.
*The  binary operation defined by the matrix in an orange background is associative and pairing it with ''A'' creates a semigroup. This is the [[Null semigroup#Left zero semigroup|left zero semigroup]] LO<sub>2</sub>. It is not commutative.
*The binary operation defined by the matrix in a purple background is associative and pairing it with ''A'' creates a semigroup. This is the [[Null semigroup#Right zero semigroup|right zero semigroup]] RO<sub>2</sub>. It is also not commutative.
*The two binary operations defined by matrices in a red background are associative and pairing either with ''A'' creates a semigroup isomorphic to the [[group (mathematics)|group]] (Z<sub>2</sub>, +<sub>2</sub>).
*The remaining eight [[binary operation]]s defined by matrices in a white background are not [[associative]] and hence none of them create a semigroup when paired with ''A''.

==The two-element semigroup ({0,1}, ∧)==
The [[Cayley table]] for the semigroup ({0,1}, <math>\wedge</math>) is given below:
<center>
{| class="wikitable" border="1"
|-
!&nbsp;<math>\wedge</math>
!&nbsp;0&nbsp;
!&nbsp;1&nbsp;
|-
|&nbsp; '''0'''&nbsp;
|&nbsp; 0&nbsp;
|&nbsp; 0&nbsp;
|-
|&nbsp; '''1'''&nbsp;
|&nbsp; 0&nbsp;
|&nbsp; 1&nbsp;
|}
</center>
This is the simplest non-trivial example of a semigroup that is not a group. This semigroup has an identity element, 1, making it a [[monoid]]. It is also commutative. It is not a group because the element 0 does not have an inverse, and is not even a cancellative semigroup because we cannot cancel the 0 in the equation 1·0 = 0·0.

This semigroup arises in various contexts. For instance, if we choose 1 to be the [[truth value]] "[[Truth|true]]" and 0 to be the [[truth value]] "[[False (logic)|false]]" and the operation to be the [[logical connective]] "[[Logical conjunction|and]]", we obtain this semigroup in [[logic]]. It is isomorphic to the monoid {0,1} under multiplication. It is also isomorphic to the semigroup
:<math> 
S = \left\{
\begin{pmatrix}
  1 & 0 \\
  0 & 1 
\end{pmatrix}, 
\begin{pmatrix}
  1 & 0 \\
  0 & 0 
\end{pmatrix}
\right\}
</math>
under [[matrix multiplication]].<ref>{{PlanetMath reference|id=8498|title=Semigroup with two elements}}</ref>

==The two-element semigroup (Z<sub>2</sub>,+<sub>2</sub>)==
The [[Cayley table]] for the semigroup (Z<sub>2</sub>,+<sub>2</sub>) is given below:
<center>
